        <h2>Methodology</h2>
        <p>
          Pioneer Pilot metagame statistics are calculated based on a deck&rsquo;s appearance in tournament Top 8s, Top 16s, Day 2s, and League 5-0 lists. We do not try to guess at the power level of a deck. Instead, the tier lists represent the prevalence of a deck in the format&mdash;and thus the likelihood that you&rsquo;ll run into it at a tournament. A deck can be a great metagame choice regardless of what tier it shows up in, though high-performing decks often get played more and begin to move up tier rankings.
        </p>
        <p>
          Our methodology is based on the fantastic <a href="http://modernnexus.com/topdecks/">Modern Nexus metagame analysis</a> that used to be publised monthly for the Modern format. Many thanks to Sheridan Lardner (ktkenshinx).
        </p>
        <h3>Data Sources</h3>
        <p>
          Pioneer metagame data is collected from multiple sources, and compiled into <a href="/">this spreadsheet</a>.
        </p>
        <p>
          The <strong>MTGO Metagame Share</strong> is compiled from a combination of: published 5-0 League decklists, which only represent a portion of the 5-0 decks (and do not reflect prevalence); and published decklists from events that <em>do</em> publish complete pictures of the metagame, including Challenge events, Magic Online Championship Series tournaments, and more.
          The <strong>Paper Metagame Share</strong> combines the following data: Top 8 and Top 16 cuts in major paper events such as the Player&rsquo;s Tour, Grand Prix, and SCG Opens&mdash;weighted heavily; Top 8 and Top 16 cuts in <em>all</em> published paper tournaments, regardless of size&mdash;weighted lightly; and Day 2 cuts in major paper events.
        </p>
        <h3>Tier Calculations</h3>
        <p>
          Decks are scored in the four categories represented in <em>Data Sources</em> above: MTGO; Major Top Cut; Major Day 2; and Minor Top Cut. A deck can be awarded from 0&ndash;3 points in each category, for a total score of up to 12 points. The point cut-off for each tier is based on the distribution of points across all decks, to ensure a reasonable distribution no matter the state of the metagame.
        </p>
